          "body": "The shift from verse 10 (gathered nations, bondage, double guilt) to verse 11 (the heifer metaphor) is more hopeful than it first appears. Hosea draws on the agricultural world his audience knew: a heifer trained to thresh loves the work because threshing is clean, unconfined, and fed by the grain that falls freely as she treads. But God says: I will come over her 'fair neck' with a yoke. The phrase 'fair neck' is unexpectedly tender — God sees the beauty of Ephraim even while putting her to harder work. The yoke is not extermination; it is redirection. Plowing is harder than threshing — it breaks ground, it prepares soil, it requires sustained exertion. But it is preparatory work, not punitive finality. Judah and Jacob are included (v.11) — the restoration vision reaching beyond the northern kingdom to embrace the entire covenant people in the coming discipline. Peter Davids and the broader prophetic tradition both note that Hosea's harshest judgment-speeches typically preserve a sliver of redemptive possibility. Here that sliver is the tenderness in 'fair neck' and the agricultural logic that plowing, however hard, makes the harvest of verse 12 possible. The yoke that seems to be destruction is actually the implement that breaks up the fallow ground the next verse will command."
